WEBVTT

00:02.461 --> 00:05.840
NARRATOR: For centuries,
mankind has been the dominant species.

00:06.006 --> 00:11.137
We've domesticated animals,
locked them up, killed them for sport.

00:11.303 --> 00:13.647
But a series of recent
events seem to suggest

00:13.805 --> 00:18.402
all across the globe animals
have decided "no more."

00:19.061 --> 00:20.233
And so we were hired,

00:20.395 --> 00:22.489
a team of people from
different backgrounds,

00:22.648 --> 00:24.491
with different specialties.

00:24.650 --> 00:26.618
An expert in animal behavior,

00:26.777 --> 00:28.074
a journalist,

00:28.237 --> 00:29.659
safari guide,

00:29.821 --> 00:31.414
foreign intelligence agent,

00:31.573 --> 00:33.792
and a veterinary pathologist.

00:33.951 --> 00:37.797
Our task: to Hnd out what is
happening with the animals,

00:37.955 --> 00:40.708
why it's happening,
and how to stop it.

00:43.126 --> 00:47.176
- Previously on Zoo:
JACKSON: That's a bat.

00:47.339 --> 00:50.388
- Flying a little high, isn't it?
- And a little too early in the day.

00:53.637 --> 00:56.561
Do you have family?
I never asked.

00:56.723 --> 00:59.101
Yeah, we're not close.

00:59.268 --> 01:03.489
As you can imagine,
I'm an acquired taste.

01:03.647 --> 01:05.820
Okay.
Why are you in Mississippi?

01:05.983 --> 01:08.156
I believe that's what you
would call classified.

01:08.318 --> 01:10.446
You know, in America,
we have this thing.

01:10.612 --> 01:12.205
It's called inter-agency
cooperation.

01:12.364 --> 01:16.915
- You should try it sometime.
- Perhaps I will, but not tonight.

01:17.077 --> 01:19.171
Good night, Agent Shafer.

01:19.705 --> 01:21.298
[WOLF ROARS AND MAN SCREAMS]

01:22.207 --> 01:23.709
MAN: Over here!

01:23.875 --> 01:25.468
[ALARM RINGING]

01:27.087 --> 01:29.089
[vvol_vEs Hovvl_lNG]

01:31.800 --> 01:32.926
Over here!

01:34.970 --> 01:36.972
MAN: Those are
Hartley's clothes.

01:38.223 --> 01:40.476
BEN: So where is Evan Lee?

01:41.018 --> 01:42.520
Well,
we've been here for two days.

01:42.686 --> 01:46.441
And already, we've discovered
unusual bacteria inside a wolf

01:46.607 --> 01:49.736
that's behaving abnormally.
That's an accomplishment.

01:50.944 --> 01:54.164
JAMIE: I found this. It's his..
Hartley's. It was in his cell.

01:54.323 --> 01:56.325
I also found this.

01:56.491 --> 01:59.665
- That Evan Lee Hartley?
- That's my father.

02:07.336 --> 02:09.008
JAMIE: Anything yet?

02:10.005 --> 02:12.758
You know what's guaranteed to
make this go faster, Jamie?

02:12.924 --> 02:15.723
You saying "anything
yet" every 25 seconds.

02:15.886 --> 02:19.106
- Okay. I know. I know, but.
- We're running out of time. I know.

02:28.815 --> 02:30.488
Here's something.

02:32.569 --> 02:36.369
Evan Lee Hartley wrote this
name all over his Bible.

02:36.531 --> 02:38.954
- Leo Butler.
- Let me see.

02:39.117 --> 02:42.917
I can't find anything to
explain why he kept this picture

02:43.080 --> 02:46.505
of him and my dad, but...

02:46.667 --> 02:49.921
Leo Butler. Here. And here.

02:50.837 --> 02:52.009
Here.

02:52.798 --> 02:54.800
Who's Leo Butler?

02:55.926 --> 02:58.145
- Hey, now. JAMIE: What?
What is it?

02:58.303 --> 03:00.397
Looks like a type of
Alcanivorax bacteria.

03:00.555 --> 03:03.900
The kind they use to clean up oil spills.
Eats hydrocarbons.

03:04.059 --> 03:07.188
Okay, well, how'd it wind
up in the blood of a wolf?

03:07.354 --> 03:08.401
The usual way.

03:08.563 --> 03:12.909
It went from a primary consumer
all the way to a tertiary consumer.

03:13.068 --> 03:14.820
Professor,
remember your audience.

03:14.986 --> 03:18.160
I spent every one of my science classes
thinking about my English homework.

03:18.323 --> 03:20.872
The food web. Chain reaction.

03:22.452 --> 03:27.003
[SINGING] There was an old
lady Who swallowed a cat.

03:27.165 --> 03:29.634
She swallowed the cat
To catch the bird.

03:29.793 --> 03:32.216
She swallowed the bird
To catch the spider.

03:33.505 --> 03:36.025
- Mitch, we really got to get going.
- That wiggled and jiggled.

03:36.049 --> 03:38.347
And tickled inside her.

03:38.510 --> 03:40.979
She swallowed the
spider To catch the fly.

03:41.138 --> 03:42.560
[BELL RINGs]

03:42.723 --> 03:45.693
- Mitch, did you hear that? Let's go.
- Hang on a second. I got something.

03:45.851 --> 03:49.196
- Mitch, we really got to go.
- Yup. On my way.

03:50.647 --> 03:52.695
We are going to get caught.
We have to get out.

03:52.858 --> 03:54.952
Mitch, move!

04:09.708 --> 04:11.255
Hey.

04:15.297 --> 04:17.265
[ENGINE STARTS]

04:17.423 --> 04:19.767
Slipping out without getting
caught by the teacher.

04:19.926 --> 04:21.519
Takes me back.

04:25.056 --> 04:27.058
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

04:30.270 --> 04:31.817
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

04:32.522 --> 04:34.650
Yeah, once I increased
the magnification,

04:34.816 --> 04:36.534
I saw a chemical signature.

04:36.693 --> 04:40.414
A string of benign molecules that have
no bearing on the bacteria whatsoever.

04:40.572 --> 04:42.540
Audience, Mitch. Remember it.

04:43.533 --> 04:45.831
It means the bacteria
was man-made.

04:46.912 --> 04:49.791
And it was signed by the
chemist who created it.

04:49.956 --> 04:53.210
- Then we need to talk to this chemist.
- Not that easy.

04:53.376 --> 04:57.051
Think of the signature
as a graffiti tag.

04:57.214 --> 05:00.343
I saw it, but I still have no
idea who painted it on the wall.

05:00.509 --> 05:02.887
- So we're at a dead end.
- Not yet.

05:03.053 --> 05:05.897
I forwarded the signature
to a guy I know at MIT.

05:06.056 --> 05:07.933
He might be able to come
up with an ID for us.

05:08.099 --> 05:10.602
Pack your bags.
We're going to Rio.

05:10.769 --> 05:14.319
- Heh. I love this job. Ha-ha-ha.
- What's in Rio?

05:14.481 --> 05:16.779
You said if you could find
out what all of these animals

05:16.942 --> 05:18.319
we've encountered
have in common,

05:18.485 --> 05:20.829
you can maybe find a way to
figure out what's happening.

05:20.987 --> 05:24.412
- Well, you can add bats to your list.
- Bats.

05:24.574 --> 05:27.999
Thousands of them swarming all over
Rio, in broad daylight.

05:28.161 --> 05:30.004
That's weird, right?

05:30.163 --> 05:31.790
What, the daylight thing?

05:31.957 --> 05:34.210
Bats are nocturnal,
but it's not unheard of.

05:34.376 --> 05:35.878
Thousands of them though?

05:36.962 --> 05:38.760
Yeah. Oh.

05:39.339 --> 05:42.138
- Excuse me, guys.
- Can I talk to you for a second?

05:46.847 --> 05:47.973
I'm not going to Rio.

05:48.139 --> 05:50.358
- Jackson...
- I'm going to find Leo Butler.

05:50.517 --> 05:52.895
You don't know that Butler
is connected to your father.

05:53.061 --> 05:54.779
And you don't know
that he's not.

05:54.938 --> 05:59.444
That was my guy at MIT.
He was able to ID the signature.

06:00.277 --> 06:03.030
It was a chemist who used
to work at Reiden Global.

06:03.196 --> 06:04.243
JAMIE: What?

06:05.532 --> 06:08.126
The company you all keep telling
me isn't the root of all evil?

06:08.285 --> 06:09.502
That Reiden Global?

06:09.661 --> 06:11.334
- Did you get a name?
- I did.

06:11.496 --> 06:14.420
- Leo Butler.
- Leo Butler?

06:14.583 --> 06:16.927
- Why? You know him?
- No.

06:17.919 --> 06:19.967
But I sure as hell want to.

06:22.215 --> 06:27.016
Okay, Jackson, you stay here with
Jamie and you find this Leo Butler.

06:27.178 --> 06:30.182
The rest of us will go to Rio.

06:31.474 --> 06:32.646
[BELL DINGs]

06:32.809 --> 06:35.437
WOMAN: The pilot has turned
off the fasten-seatbelt sign.

06:35.604 --> 06:37.606
You're free to roam
about the cabin.

06:37.772 --> 06:39.695
They can't fly this
high, you know.

06:40.400 --> 06:42.494
Bats. They can't fly this high.

06:42.652 --> 06:45.952
You were flying at a much lower
altitude when they came at you in Japan

06:46.114 --> 06:49.618
so nothing to worry about.
At least until we start our descent.

06:49.784 --> 06:55.211
Meantime, in order to keep
your mind off all things bat,

06:55.373 --> 06:59.048
I thought, uh,
I'd offer up some facts.

07:00.003 --> 07:02.677
- Facts about what?
- Facts about bats.

07:02.839 --> 07:04.841
- Bat fact number one.
- Oh, God.

07:05.008 --> 07:07.261
Their wings are
actually webbed fingers.

07:07.427 --> 07:09.646
Bat fact number two.

07:09.804 --> 07:12.182
The phrase "blind as a
bat," kind of a misnomer.

07:12.349 --> 07:13.629
I mean, they don't see too well,

07:13.767 --> 07:16.987
but same can be said for some of
us, right?

07:19.189 --> 07:21.533
Word on the street is Butler
has been blackmailing Reiden

07:21.691 --> 07:22.908
ever since he went underground

07:23.068 --> 07:24.911
and dispersing the money
to various charities,

07:25.070 --> 07:27.368
charities all over the world
that give the money to people

07:27.530 --> 07:29.874
who've been wronged by Reiden.

07:30.033 --> 07:33.207
- Are these internal Reiden documents?
- I've made some friends over the years.

07:33.370 --> 07:35.964
Bloggers. Hacktivists.
People under the stairs.

07:36.122 --> 07:39.547
- But they got us these.
- This is completely illegal.

07:40.919 --> 07:42.091
I like it.

07:43.254 --> 07:45.632
- Okay, well, we have to find him.
- I'm getting close.

07:45.799 --> 07:48.769
A guy's gotta live while he's out
there being Robin Hood, right?

07:49.761 --> 07:52.731
Butler has been paying himself with
a portion of the blackmail money,

07:52.889 --> 07:54.266
routing it through
shell companies

07:54.432 --> 07:56.025
with PO boxes all
over the Gulf Coast.

07:56.184 --> 08:00.064
I think with a little time and some
luck I can get his actual address.

08:01.272 --> 08:02.444
Wow.

08:02.607 --> 08:04.530
This is... This is good.

08:05.068 --> 08:06.661
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

08:13.118 --> 08:15.120
Miss Campbell.
Agent Shafer with the FBI.

08:15.286 --> 08:17.880
- We met at the prison.
- Yes, of course. Agent Shafer.

08:19.916 --> 08:22.135
I see what you did there.

08:22.293 --> 08:23.920
You said my name
louder than necessary

08:24.087 --> 08:26.135
as if to alert somebody in
your room of my presence.

08:26.297 --> 08:27.924
Yeah, my subterfuge
game isn't so tight.

08:28.091 --> 08:31.186
- Well, frankly, it's terrible.
- How'd you know we were here?

08:31.344 --> 08:33.224
Miss Tousignant asked me
to keep her in the loop

08:33.388 --> 08:36.357
on the Evan Lee Hartley manhunt.
She told me where you'd be staying.

08:36.515 --> 08:39.190
Agent Shafer. Please, come in.

08:39.352 --> 08:41.104
- Great.
- No. Jackson, I don't think...

08:41.270 --> 08:44.741
Ahem. So have you found him?
Hartley?

08:44.899 --> 08:46.242
I didn't say that.

08:46.401 --> 08:48.950
I implied it so you'd let me in.

08:49.112 --> 08:51.535
See,
his subterfuge game is tight.

08:51.698 --> 08:53.700
Well,
I am a trained professional.

08:53.867 --> 08:55.119
What do you want?

08:56.369 --> 08:59.168
What does Reiden Global have
to do with the prison fire?

09:02.000 --> 09:03.217
Why do you ask that?

09:03.376 --> 09:05.003
Well,
Reiden was hacked yesterday

09:05.170 --> 09:08.515
and somehow, some of their
documents found their way

09:08.673 --> 09:10.220
into your e-mail address.

09:10.383 --> 09:13.102
- How...?
- We have a Cybercrime division.

09:13.261 --> 09:14.478
We're good like that.

09:14.637 --> 09:17.811
So first, I find you scam your
way into a crime scene ata prison

09:17.974 --> 09:20.978
and now,
you've hacked into Reiden Global.

09:21.144 --> 09:24.569
So how about you tell me
what you're really up to?

09:27.025 --> 09:28.572
[SIGHS]

09:28.985 --> 09:32.330
I have a friend at the
Brazilian Intelligence Agency.

09:32.489 --> 09:34.958
When we arrive in Rio,
she will brief us on the situation.

09:36.076 --> 09:38.124
Sounds like a plan.
Proud to be part of it.

09:38.286 --> 09:40.446
MAN: Ladies and gentlemen,
we are beginning our descent

09:40.497 --> 09:43.171
into lovely Rio de Janeiro.

09:43.958 --> 09:45.460
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

09:45.627 --> 09:47.004
What is it?

09:47.170 --> 09:50.049
All flight attendants,
please return to your seats.

09:54.344 --> 09:56.392
MITCH: Bat fact number three.

09:57.806 --> 10:00.025
Apparently,
it's worse than we thought.

10:50.108 --> 10:52.281
Ah. Joey cut his hair.

10:52.443 --> 10:53.569
Can you believe that, Henry?

10:55.405 --> 10:57.908
Oh. Here's something
about Tristan.

10:58.074 --> 11:01.123
It says he has a black
lab named Esther.

11:01.286 --> 11:04.381
It'd be fun to go out
with a boy who had a dog.

11:04.539 --> 11:07.543
Or even a boy who
didn't have a dog.

11:08.877 --> 11:11.175
Okay. Good boy, Henry.

11:13.923 --> 11:15.766
[Dos BARKING]

11:22.223 --> 11:24.521
[WOMAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

11:27.312 --> 11:28.609
You okay?

11:33.026 --> 11:35.905
Sweetie? Okay, baby, come on.

11:42.827 --> 11:46.172
MAN: You okay, kiddo? - Yeah.

11:47.081 --> 11:49.254
It wasn't a bad one.

11:49.876 --> 11:51.878
And Henry warned me in time.

11:55.590 --> 11:56.762
MAN: Good boy.

12:05.391 --> 12:07.109
Hey, you know,
you can't just arrest him

12:07.268 --> 12:09.145
before we've had a
chance to talk with him.

12:09.312 --> 12:11.565
BEN: Sure I can.
In fact, I have to.

12:11.731 --> 12:13.825
Once I called the Bureau
to pinpoint Leo's location

12:13.983 --> 12:17.408
from a list of PO boxes,
it became an official FBI investigation.

12:17.570 --> 12:18.913
Even has a case number.

12:19.072 --> 12:21.166
You have to give me 15
minutes with him first.

12:21.324 --> 12:24.123
Look, I already agreed to let you
come along on this little boat ride.

12:24.285 --> 12:27.414
- Now you're giving me orders?
- Fifteen minutes. That's all we ask.

12:27.580 --> 12:28.877
Miss Campbell, you just told me

12:29.040 --> 12:31.793
that Leo Butler's blackmailing
a multinational corporation.

12:31.960 --> 12:33.257
It's a federal offense.

12:33.419 --> 12:35.467
Out of everything we told
you, that's your takeaway?

12:35.630 --> 12:37.974
Federal crime,
Federal Bureau of Investigation.

12:38.132 --> 12:39.224
You see the linkage?

12:39.384 --> 12:41.784
How about the fact that when
this guy was working for Reiden,

12:41.928 --> 12:44.101
somehow Leo Butler
created a bacteria

12:44.264 --> 12:46.437
that caused those wolves
to attack a prison?

12:46.599 --> 12:47.691
Let's see.

12:47.850 --> 12:50.319
Leo Butler, a blackmailing
embezzler, invents a bacteria

12:50.478 --> 12:52.981
that accidentally creates
prisoner-eating wolves.

12:53.147 --> 12:55.347
That's what you want me to
tell my bosses at the Bureau?

12:55.483 --> 12:57.235
That's a better takeaway?

13:03.032 --> 13:05.112
CHLOE: We want to know what
is driving the bats wild.

13:05.243 --> 13:06.415
WOMAN: So do we.

13:06.577 --> 13:08.454
What business is that of
the French government?

13:08.621 --> 13:10.464
I'm sorry. I cannot say it.

13:10.623 --> 13:13.001
State secrets. Of course.

13:13.167 --> 13:15.261
In any case,
it's nice to see you in the field.

13:15.420 --> 13:17.514
Congratulations.

13:17.672 --> 13:21.017
So the bats.
Have your scientists done any testing?

13:21.175 --> 13:23.428
Sim. And the good news,
they have determined the bats

13:23.594 --> 13:26.438
- do not have rabies.
- And the bad news?

13:26.597 --> 13:29.976
Rabies is the only thing that would
even come close to explaining this.

13:30.143 --> 13:31.269
Your friend is a scientist.

13:31.436 --> 13:34.531
One who would love to know what
responses are being considered.

13:35.690 --> 13:38.990
The plan on the table is to drop
a version of endrin on the bats.

13:39.944 --> 13:43.414
Endrin? Come on.
You can't be serious.

13:43.573 --> 13:46.076
- What is endrin?
MITCH: it's an insecticide.

13:46.242 --> 13:49.121
Outlawed in the States and
most developed countries.

13:49.287 --> 13:52.541
It's like chemotherapy. Kills the cancer
but attacks everything else as well.

13:52.707 --> 13:55.381
You do realize you'd
be risking the health

13:55.543 --> 13:57.545
of every single
living thing in Rio.

13:57.712 --> 13:59.589
And we are considering
that very issue.

13:59.756 --> 14:02.726
But you've seen the bats.
People are frightened.

14:02.884 --> 14:04.386
Well,
at least give us some time.

14:04.552 --> 14:07.601
Because if you kill them all, we'll
never learn what's causing this behavior.

14:08.681 --> 14:10.058
- I'll do what I can.
- Thank you.

14:10.224 --> 14:11.271
But I make no promises.

14:13.019 --> 14:14.817
[ENGINE STARTS]

14:16.606 --> 14:21.578
You know, I can't help but notice
for a city under siege by bats...

14:21.736 --> 14:23.158
No bats.

14:24.947 --> 14:26.790
Not here, at least.

14:28.993 --> 14:31.416
CHLOE: Why over
there and not here?

15:06.572 --> 15:09.200
Hey, wait. We can't go in there.
We don't have a warrant.

15:10.284 --> 15:12.127
Good thing I'm not a cop.

15:18.918 --> 15:21.467
- What's the cage for?
JAMIE: Damned if I know.

15:27.051 --> 15:28.974
[FOOTSTEPS]

15:32.640 --> 15:35.320
- Federal agent. We just wanna talk.
JAMIE: We don't wanna hurt you.

15:40.523 --> 15:42.992
Or maybe we do just
wanna hurt you.

15:46.821 --> 15:50.997
MITCH: Come to Rio,
jewel of South America.

15:55.997 --> 15:58.091
I've seen this before,

15:58.249 --> 16:02.129
this kind ofjerry-rigged power,
in poorer African villages.

16:02.295 --> 16:04.889
This place might as
well be a separate city,

16:05.047 --> 16:07.220
cut off from all
official services.

16:07.383 --> 16:12.389
Utilities, plumbing,
power, telephone service.

16:12.555 --> 16:15.229
To survive,
the people are forced to improvise.

16:15.683 --> 16:18.562
Why do you suppose the bats
congregate here, of all places?

16:18.728 --> 16:21.106
Because it's less sanitary here?

16:21.272 --> 16:23.821
More insects?
More food for the bats?

16:23.983 --> 16:27.829
I don't know. I gotta get ahold of one
of these things, study it up close.

16:27.987 --> 16:31.708
Gabriela was able to delay the
pesticide drop until morning.

16:32.867 --> 16:34.710
Still doesn't give us much
time, does it?

16:34.869 --> 16:37.247
[GuNl=lRE]

16:39.624 --> 16:41.184
It's okay.
They're shooting at the bats.

16:47.548 --> 16:49.175
Mitch.

16:53.387 --> 16:55.185
After you.

17:27.296 --> 17:29.719
[BATS sQuEAKING]

17:31.133 --> 17:33.101
CHLOE: What are they doing?

17:34.762 --> 17:36.139
[SIGHS]

17:36.305 --> 17:38.558
Sometimes insects like
to nest in transformers.

17:38.724 --> 17:40.726
Maybe the bats are feeding.

17:48.776 --> 17:51.655
CHLOE: What? ABRAHAM: Get down!

17:57.785 --> 17:59.879
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

18:05.710 --> 18:07.963
Must have been a chain reaction.

18:29.025 --> 18:30.277
[SPEAKS IN PORTUGUESE]

18:30.443 --> 18:31.660
- What did you do?
- Nothing.

18:31.819 --> 18:33.571
We're only studying the bats.

18:34.989 --> 18:37.583
- You're French?
- Yes.

18:37.742 --> 18:40.746
My friend,
we don't want any trouble.

18:40.911 --> 18:43.084
And where are you
from, big papa?

18:43.748 --> 18:45.216
Africa.

18:46.542 --> 18:47.885
Gonna wish you never left.

18:49.045 --> 18:51.047
You might want to reconsider.

18:51.213 --> 18:53.090
[SPEAKS IN PORTUGUESE]

19:06.354 --> 19:09.324
Shall we lower our weapons
and have a discussion?

19:10.983 --> 19:16.990
An American, an African,
and a French woman.

19:20.076 --> 19:21.453
[MAN CHUCKLES]

19:26.082 --> 19:30.883
If you'd walk into a bar together,
we'd have the beginning of a bad joke.

19:31.545 --> 19:35.721
Rio has many sights popular
with the tourists but, uh...

19:35.883 --> 19:38.306
This neighborhood
is not one of them.

19:39.303 --> 19:42.773
Tell your men to stand down.
We're no threat to them.

19:44.475 --> 19:47.979
The fact that your gun is
still raised says otherwise.

19:49.897 --> 19:52.992
Chloe, please lower your gun.

19:55.528 --> 19:58.657
Perhaps we should pay
these men for their time.

19:58.823 --> 20:03.169
A token of our
inconveniencing them.

20:04.787 --> 20:06.881
You have been around.

20:08.165 --> 20:09.758
Here and there.

20:11.460 --> 20:12.507
That's wonderful.

20:38.362 --> 20:40.080
Souvenir.

20:44.618 --> 20:48.498
Look, just tell us what you
know about Evan Lee Hartley.

20:48.664 --> 20:51.042
I don't know who that is.

20:51.208 --> 20:55.133
Your name is written on almost
every other page of his Bible.

20:55.296 --> 20:57.424
Well, that's suitably eerie.

20:58.674 --> 21:01.769
What about Robert Oz? Robert Oz.
Does that ring any bells?

21:01.927 --> 21:05.056
Oz. No. Should it?
Are you gonna hit me again?

21:05.222 --> 21:09.648
Jackson. Please.
Look, we need your help.

21:09.810 --> 21:11.904
Please, can you just talk to us?

21:12.062 --> 21:14.781
So if she's the good cop
and he's the bad cop,

21:14.940 --> 21:17.318
- what does that make you?
- Oh, actually, I'm the only cop.

21:17.485 --> 21:19.579
We need to talk to you
about Reiden Global.

21:19.737 --> 21:22.456
- No. No. No way.
- Leo, please.

21:22.615 --> 21:27.337
No way. I'm not getting involved in this.
They've got people everywhere.

21:27.495 --> 21:29.122
You could be involved with them.

21:29.288 --> 21:32.041
Leo, I'm from Folsom, Louisiana.

21:32.208 --> 21:35.758
- Does that mean anything to you?
- Of course.

21:35.920 --> 21:37.968
There's a brand-new library
there because of you.

21:38.130 --> 21:40.724
I heard it came out beautiful.

21:40.883 --> 21:44.888
What can you tell us about
the Alcanivorax bacteria?

21:50.559 --> 21:52.937
What is taking him so
long to find Henry?

21:53.103 --> 21:55.276
You let the dog out again
with the fence still broken

21:55.439 --> 21:57.817
and you're gonna complain that
your stepdad hasn't found him

21:57.983 --> 22:00.202
- in a timely fashion?
- I know, I know.

22:00.361 --> 22:02.489
I just keep forgetting
that it's not fixed.

22:02.655 --> 22:05.374
- When will it be fixed?
- When I hit the lottery.

22:05.533 --> 22:08.286
That would be such a great
story, it would make the news.

22:08.452 --> 22:12.377
"I\/Iother of a dying girl wins big.
Story at 11:00."

22:12.540 --> 22:13.757
Clementine.

22:13.916 --> 22:15.463
You'd be famous,
and me and Henry too.

22:15.626 --> 22:17.128
I don't wanna be
famous for that.

22:18.295 --> 22:20.263
[CELL PHONE CHIMING]

22:22.800 --> 22:23.892
Hello?

22:24.051 --> 22:26.429
Henry got hit by a car
on Cranston Street.

22:26.595 --> 22:28.063
I'm on my way to the vet now.

22:28.222 --> 22:33.444
- Oh, God.
- What is it? What is it, Mom?

22:37.982 --> 22:40.405
ABRAHAM: What are you looking
for, exactly?

22:41.527 --> 22:43.996
Anything abnormal.

22:44.154 --> 22:46.532
Some sort of clue as to why
they're behaving this way.

22:46.699 --> 22:47.871
Could take a while.

22:48.033 --> 22:50.127
That's why I never had
any patience for science.

22:51.036 --> 22:53.084
I'm going to walk
to that pastéis.

22:53.247 --> 22:56.296
- Does anybody want something?
- No, I'm good.

22:56.458 --> 22:59.382
- Chloe?
- I'm good. Thank you.

23:14.226 --> 23:16.479
I didn't want to say
anything in front of Abe,

23:16.645 --> 23:21.367
but when your friend was talking
earlier, uh, Gabriela,

23:21.525 --> 23:24.620
about seeing you in the
field, what was that about?

23:25.821 --> 23:30.543
- I've not seen her in a long time is all.
- Yeah, I don't think that's it.

23:30.701 --> 23:34.922
Not seeing how you played
it with those street kids.

23:35.080 --> 23:38.880
Might have been nice if you
or your boss would've told us

23:39.043 --> 23:41.421
that our field leader
has no field experience.

23:42.880 --> 23:45.850
I'm entirely qualified for
whatever we may encounter

23:46.008 --> 23:47.601
while carrying out this mission.

23:47.760 --> 23:50.479
Yeah, see, even that sounds like
you read it out of a spy novel.

23:50.638 --> 23:51.890
[SCOFFS]

23:53.474 --> 23:56.193
Someday,
I would like to meet this person

23:56.352 --> 23:58.150
who made you become this
thing you are today.

23:59.188 --> 24:01.691
Was it his mom,
who didn't hug him enough?

24:01.857 --> 24:04.235
A college girlfriend
who broke his heart?

24:04.401 --> 24:07.951
Or was he always the last
picked on the sporting teams?

24:09.782 --> 24:11.750
It was all those things.

24:15.788 --> 24:16.835
Hang on a second.

24:18.582 --> 24:22.382
The eyes have changed.
Shape is different.

24:23.295 --> 24:26.970
Here, come here. Take a look.
Pupils are bigger.

24:29.176 --> 24:31.349
[BAT SHRIEKS AND CHLOE GASPS]

24:32.012 --> 24:34.561
That's not dead.
That is not a dead bat.

24:34.723 --> 24:38.068
That... Definitely not.

24:38.227 --> 24:42.653
So you mimicked the wolf's
brain inside a coffee pot?

24:42.815 --> 24:44.988
"That's actually"
That's quite brilliant.

24:45.150 --> 24:47.152
Our brilliance really
isn't the message here.

24:47.319 --> 24:52.325
- And then the coffee pot exploded?
- Literally.

24:52.491 --> 24:54.414
Oh, galloping crud.

24:54.576 --> 24:56.920
Okay, kiddies.
You've had your coffee klatch.

24:57.079 --> 24:59.958
- Time for Loopy Leo to go to jail.
- No, no, ten minutes.

25:00.124 --> 25:03.970
- I'll give you four.
- Jail? Who said anything about jail?

25:04.128 --> 25:06.256
Leo,
could the bacteria you created

25:06.422 --> 25:08.174
have caused the wolves'
behavior to change?

25:08.340 --> 25:12.766
No. Not the bacteria.

25:12.928 --> 25:15.772
Leo, please, if there's something
that you know, just tell us.

25:16.598 --> 25:20.068
Look, a lot of guys would not
have given that money to charity.

25:20.227 --> 25:22.446
I know you're one
of the good ones.

25:24.398 --> 25:28.244
Ever wonder why Reiden is
so much more successful

25:28.402 --> 25:30.825
than all of their competitors?

25:30.988 --> 25:34.288
It's because they have a vector
that's better than all the others.

25:34.992 --> 25:36.369
- Really? BEN: Okay.

25:36.535 --> 25:39.163
I'll be man enough to admit it.
I wouldn't know what a vector is

25:39.329 --> 25:41.377
even if the Wi-Fi in this
creepy shack was working.

25:41.540 --> 25:46.216
A vector is a DNA molecule used
to manipulate cellular material

25:46.378 --> 25:47.425
on a genetic level.

25:47.588 --> 25:50.137
Still haven't gotten any smarter
in the last five seconds.

25:50.299 --> 25:52.267
It means they have a molecule

25:52.426 --> 25:56.306
that allows them to be
faster, better, cheaper.

25:56.472 --> 25:58.315
Why doesn't everybody
else just get their own?

25:58.474 --> 26:00.226
Because they can't.

26:00.392 --> 26:04.238
Among other things,
the vector is extremely rare.

26:04.396 --> 26:07.946
Outside of Reiden, you are the only
other people who know it exists.

26:08.108 --> 26:11.237
Only a select few inside Reiden
even know where it comes from.

26:11.403 --> 26:15.408
- They call it the Mother Cell.
- That doesn't sound ominous at all.

26:15.574 --> 26:17.918
LEO: They discovered it
about a dozen years ago.

26:18.077 --> 26:20.876
Preliminary testing proved
how powerful it was.

26:21.038 --> 26:24.212
By the time they realized the potential
side effects, it was too late.

26:24.374 --> 26:26.923
They'd already invested
too much money to back out.

26:27.086 --> 26:30.431
- What side effects?
- I don't sleep anymore,

26:30.589 --> 26:32.262
because I lay awake at night

26:32.424 --> 26:35.394
counting all the different
ways they could kill me.

26:35.552 --> 26:36.929
I'd arrived at 16.

26:37.096 --> 26:40.066
- Sixteen different ways.
- Leo! Side effects.

26:40.224 --> 26:43.023
It's doing something to the
animals, isn't it?

26:44.103 --> 26:46.947
Do you know where it
is used by Reiden?

26:48.565 --> 26:50.613
Maybe you don't understand.

26:51.735 --> 26:57.742
The Mother Cell is in every
single product Reiden makes.

26:57.908 --> 27:02.038
It's everywhere. It's all over the
world, and it can't be stopped.

27:11.630 --> 27:13.132
JAMIE: No one is gonna hurt you.

27:13.298 --> 27:15.676
Just get us the Mother Cell
and all of this will be over.

27:15.843 --> 27:17.811
We can protect you.
Right, Agent Shafer?

27:17.970 --> 27:19.017
Absolutely.

27:23.767 --> 27:26.190
I keep it hidden,
not far from here.

27:26.353 --> 27:28.856
- Fine. We're going with you.
- No. Absolutely not.

27:29.022 --> 27:30.444
You don't have a
say in the matter.

27:30.607 --> 27:34.362
I certainly do.
I just won't retrieve it for you.

27:34.528 --> 27:36.371
Well,
then you can just go to jail.

27:37.489 --> 27:40.163
That still doesn't get
you the Mother Cell.

27:40.325 --> 27:42.578
Wait, what if I went with you?
Just me.

27:42.744 --> 27:45.042
One of you guys punched him
and the other one's a cop.

27:45.205 --> 27:47.924
- I would under.
- That would be entirely acceptable.

27:49.918 --> 27:52.842
- It would?
- Entirely.

27:55.090 --> 27:56.262
We'll take my boat.

28:00.053 --> 28:03.557
- Vet says it'll cost $3,000.
- Three thousand?

28:03.724 --> 28:05.818
He's gonna need
follow-up surgery.

28:07.769 --> 28:09.521
On top of Clem's treatment?

28:11.732 --> 28:12.949
How can we?

28:14.401 --> 28:16.824
You're not gonna like this,

28:16.987 --> 28:18.580
- but maybe we should call him.
- No.

28:18.739 --> 28:20.582
- Aud, I'm just saying.
- Why?

28:20.741 --> 28:23.585
- Because he bought her the dog?
- He is her father.

28:23.744 --> 28:26.998
She hasn't seen him since
she was 2 years old.

28:27.164 --> 28:31.169
No, I am not gonna call him and
guilt him into paying for this.

28:33.086 --> 28:36.636
Okay. We'll go to Plan B.

28:36.798 --> 28:41.053
- We have a Plan B?
- Sure.

28:42.095 --> 28:44.439
Plan B is we make it work.

28:45.933 --> 28:48.027
We'll fix Henry and
we'll figure it out.

28:48.185 --> 28:50.984
But we are not gonna let
Clem lose her best friend.

29:01.323 --> 29:02.620
[SIGHS]

29:04.618 --> 29:06.120
[sQuEAKING]

29:06.286 --> 29:08.630
Why are you so anxious?

29:10.791 --> 29:14.011
Still not sure letting her go alone
with that guy was the right thing to do.

29:14.169 --> 29:18.015
Oh, please.
You see the way he looked at her?

29:18.173 --> 29:20.847
Like he'd been wandering the
Sahara Desert for five years

29:21.009 --> 29:23.637
- and she was a lake of root beer.
- Huh?

29:24.263 --> 29:27.483
It means he may ditch her,
but he's not gonna hurt her.

29:27.641 --> 29:32.647
- Butjust in case, bang.
- What?

29:32.813 --> 29:34.156
I hacked into Leo's account.

29:34.314 --> 29:35.987
Now, he syncs his phone
with his computer,

29:36.149 --> 29:38.368
so I can access the
GPS on his phone.

29:38.527 --> 29:40.279
- You hacked into the account?
- Yeah.

29:40.445 --> 29:42.118
What kind of a
federal agent are you?

29:42.281 --> 29:44.124
A good one.
All right, that's them.

29:44.283 --> 29:47.332
If he's able to ditch Jamie and
disappear with the Mother Cell,

29:47.494 --> 29:48.620
we can track him.

29:48.787 --> 29:49.959
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

29:50.122 --> 29:53.001
You know what,
keep an eye on them, will you?

29:57.212 --> 30:02.093
- Hello?
- Hello, Jackson? It's Chloe.

30:02.259 --> 30:03.852
- How are things in Rio?
- Good, good.

30:04.344 --> 30:05.470
Um...

30:05.637 --> 30:08.311
It's quiet. At the moment.

30:08.473 --> 30:10.396
Mitch is examining a bat.

30:10.559 --> 30:13.733
He discovered an
abnormality in its eye.

30:13.895 --> 30:17.570
I swear to God, I am gonna kill
that man before this is over.

30:17.733 --> 30:19.531
Yeah, I may beat you to it.

30:19.693 --> 30:22.617
And Abraham,
he has his dark places, no?

30:22.779 --> 30:27.125
Oui. Yeah. Perhaps someday
he'll tell you about it.

30:27.284 --> 30:29.457
So did you End Leo Butler?

30:29.619 --> 30:32.168
Yeah, we did.
He doesn't know my father.

30:32.331 --> 30:34.550
But listen to this. He may...

30:34.708 --> 30:35.960
[GAsPING]

30:36.126 --> 30:40.723
Chloe? Hey, what's going on over there?
You okay?

30:41.882 --> 30:44.431
Hey, Chloe. Hey, Chloe.

30:44.593 --> 30:49.394
- Chloe?
- I'm sorry, I have to go.

30:51.725 --> 30:55.446
Is it possible that the bat was
attracted to my phone or to technology?

30:55.604 --> 30:56.696
I mean, is that crazy?

30:57.606 --> 31:00.826
Well, crazy seems to be on a
sliding scale since I met you guys.

31:00.984 --> 31:03.863
The plane in Japan. Perhaps the bats
were attracted to its radio waves.

31:04.029 --> 31:06.873
And what about the solar
panels in the Antarctic?

31:07.032 --> 31:10.286
And those power poles in the
favelas weren't shielded properly.

31:10.452 --> 31:12.500
I think you are using
the wrong words.

31:12.662 --> 31:16.633
Being attracted to something is
not the same thing as attacking it.

31:16.792 --> 31:20.217
Well, I don't know. I once threw all
my ex-wife's clothes on the front lawn

31:20.379 --> 31:22.677
because I was attracted to her.

31:23.590 --> 31:26.059
All right, are you guys
familiar with the trophic scale?

31:26.218 --> 31:27.344
Well, pretend we're not.

31:27.511 --> 31:30.406
The trophic scale is an index of where
everything falls on the food chain.

31:30.430 --> 31:33.274
Apex predators are a five.
They're at the top.

31:33.433 --> 31:38.189
Sharks, tigers, birds of prey.
Predators that eat other predators.

31:38.355 --> 31:43.532
Humans, contrary to popular
belief, are only a 2.2.

31:43.693 --> 31:47.948
Alongside pigs and anchovies.

31:48.115 --> 31:49.412
Anchovies.

31:49.574 --> 31:55.172
Now, only two things allow
us to behave like fives.

31:55.914 --> 31:57.040
Our ability to reason...

31:59.876 --> 32:00.923
And our technology.

32:09.594 --> 32:11.016
They're still on the move.

32:11.179 --> 32:14.023
Looks like they docked his boat.
Now they're in his car.

32:16.726 --> 32:18.478
What are you doing?

32:18.645 --> 32:22.650
Leo Butler's name is written all
over Evan Lee Hartley's Bible.

32:22.816 --> 32:24.443
Maybe something in
here will tell me why.

32:24.609 --> 32:25.986
Hold on.
We don't have a warrant,

32:26.153 --> 32:29.202
- so none of this can be used in court.
- Spare me the ethics lecture, okay?

32:29.364 --> 32:31.537
You just hacked into
the man's computer.

32:32.659 --> 32:35.082
I'll start on this stuff.

32:42.419 --> 32:45.013
But they can't know it.
The animals, the bats.

32:45.172 --> 32:46.549
Can't know what?

32:46.715 --> 32:50.185
That's it's only our technology
that keeps us from being their prey.

32:50.343 --> 32:53.187
Are you asking if the animals
have somehow developed

32:53.346 --> 32:55.769
a hyper-intelligence?

32:55.932 --> 32:57.275
Whether they know it or not,

32:57.434 --> 33:01.359
this mission of ours has just
become a whole lot less amusing.

33:01.521 --> 33:05.321
- How far can bats see?
- Ahem. Depends.

33:05.484 --> 33:09.830
Some can only see 25 feet, others can
see up to a few hundred yards. Why?

33:09.988 --> 33:12.332
We go far out into the forest

33:12.491 --> 33:16.166
and we hook up something with
an electromagnetic signal,

33:16.328 --> 33:18.751
and we boost it somehow
so the bats can't miss it.

33:18.914 --> 33:23.670
Once there, they'll be too far away to
see any other electromagnetic source.

33:23.835 --> 33:25.883
Exactement.
So maybe they remain there.

33:26.046 --> 33:28.640
All right. Whoa. Whoa.

33:28.798 --> 33:30.846
Let's try and remember our
designations here, okay?

33:31.009 --> 33:35.435
I'm the scientist. You're the analyst.
Still not sure what you are.

33:35.597 --> 33:39.522
- But it could work, yes?
- No. Yes.

33:40.644 --> 33:44.444
Maybe. If we... If we had something
that gave off that kind of signal.

33:44.606 --> 33:48.531
How about a cellular antenna?
Like the one at the favela?

33:48.693 --> 33:49.785
The favelas...

33:49.945 --> 33:52.198
Yeah, you don't remember what
happened to us out there?

33:52.364 --> 33:54.787
Real cellular antennae,
those owned by phone companies,

33:54.950 --> 33:57.829
- will be secured behind locked gates.
- No. No way.

33:57.994 --> 34:01.840
- Do you have another idea?
- You support this plan?

34:03.833 --> 34:04.880
Yes.

34:06.211 --> 34:08.634
I mean, guys,
we have to do something.

34:08.797 --> 34:11.516
If we don't, the government
will drop poison from the sky,

34:11.675 --> 34:13.052
and as you yourself pointed out,

34:13.217 --> 34:17.643
that poison will affect every
living thing in Rio. Including us.

34:41.204 --> 34:43.002
Stay here.

34:44.916 --> 34:49.797
- Where are you going?
- To get it. The Mother Cell.

34:52.632 --> 34:54.259
Almost forgot.

35:45.727 --> 35:49.277
- What are you doing?
- Contributing.

35:49.439 --> 35:52.693
I'm gonna sell some of this stuff to
help pay for Henry's doctor bills.

35:52.859 --> 35:56.238
Sweetie, don't be ridiculous.

35:57.947 --> 35:59.494
Wait.

36:00.575 --> 36:04.125
- Where did you get this?
- From your closet.

36:04.287 --> 36:05.664
I didn't know I still had it.

36:06.998 --> 36:11.720
- You know I love Justin, Mom, right?
- I know.

36:13.004 --> 36:18.386
- But do you think if I got really bad.
- Baby.

36:18.551 --> 36:20.178
That he would come?

36:20.345 --> 36:22.143
- Clementine.
- Do you?

36:23.807 --> 36:27.607
I don't know. I really don't.

36:28.937 --> 36:32.316
JUSTIN: Hey, guys. Here, boy.
- It's them.

36:34.818 --> 36:37.037
- Is he okay?
- He's gonna be fine.

36:37.195 --> 36:39.618
He just needs to take it easy
for a while and take his meds.

36:39.781 --> 36:43.285
- Welcome to my world, Henry.
- Exactly, babe.

36:43.451 --> 36:45.328
And I'm putting you in charge.

36:45.495 --> 36:47.497
Just like you're good
about taking your medicine,

36:47.664 --> 36:49.632
you gotta be good
about giving Henry his.

36:49.791 --> 36:52.465
I can do that.
Thank you so much, guys.

36:53.586 --> 36:56.214
Thank you so much.

36:56.381 --> 37:00.932
He must be starving.
Come on, Henry. Time for supper.

37:01.553 --> 37:03.100
Come on.

37:05.598 --> 37:07.396
Whew. Thank you.

37:08.601 --> 37:12.322
Plan B. Make your kid smile.

37:13.314 --> 37:15.316
Everything else will
take care of itself.

37:56.149 --> 37:59.744
- Hold on.
- What is it?

38:01.404 --> 38:07.502
Looks like some sort of inventory of
products that contain the Mother Cell.

38:08.119 --> 38:12.090
And how and where those
products were used.

38:15.585 --> 38:17.587
You're telling me that
all of these products

38:17.754 --> 38:19.301
have this Mother Cell in them?

38:20.131 --> 38:25.513
But this is everything from
dog food to weed killer.

38:26.679 --> 38:27.931
I know.

38:32.310 --> 38:34.312
[OWL l-looTIN<3]

38:41.110 --> 38:42.487
[GASPS]

38:55.625 --> 38:56.672
Wow.

38:57.335 --> 38:59.383
LEO: I know, right?

39:01.464 --> 39:06.220
I gotta admit,
I'm kind of glad to be shed of it.

39:06.386 --> 39:11.233
Soon as I pack up my stuff,
I disappear, for good.

39:11.391 --> 39:13.234
Now it's your problem.

39:13.393 --> 39:14.940
[ENGINE STARTS]

39:36.499 --> 39:38.752
[ALARM souNDING]

39:46.092 --> 39:47.344
[ENGINE STARTS]

39:53.016 --> 39:54.609
Got the truck.
Be there in five minutes.

39:54.767 --> 39:56.019
We'll be ready.

39:57.353 --> 39:59.526
Think I almost got it.

40:01.316 --> 40:03.068
MAN: Almost got what?

40:03.234 --> 40:07.990
I can't even begin to understand
what's happening right now. Do not.

40:09.115 --> 40:11.493
You're making a mistake.

40:12.827 --> 40:15.421
Only mistake was keeping
Enzo on his leash earlier.

40:15.580 --> 40:18.049
- Hidey-ho. MITCH: Hey.

40:18.750 --> 40:22.596
We're... We're actually just
trying to solve your bat problem.

